### Tested versions

- Reproducible in: master (c2202d36c10661873fb729bcf9c4c00b99e10c7a), 4.4.1.stable.mono, 4.3.stable.mono

### System information

Godot v4.4.1.stable.mono - Fedora Linux 42 (Workstation Edition) on Wayland - X11 display driver, Single-window, 2 monitors - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated AMD Radeon RX 6900 XT (RADV NAVI21) - AMD Ryzen 9 5950X 16-Core Processor (32 threads)

### Issue description

Everything appears to work fine, but I get these errors in the debugger window both when launching the game or when reloading the project, since the custom Visual Shader nodes are global classes and tools.  The error appears as the following: 
```
E 0:00:03:476   get_output_port_type: Index p_port = 4 is out of bounds (output_ports.size() = 1).
  <C++ Source>  scene/resources/visual_shader.cpp:606 @ get_output_port_type()
```
While the shader node itself seems to function, this kind of error is misleading/incorrect behavior, especially since the end result visually looks correct.

### Steps to reproduce

1) Create a custom visual shader node, that uses an output that has an expansion option out of the box such as Vector4D, where it can be expanded to output each of its channels.  The following is an example I used:

```C#
using Godot;
using Godot.Collections;
using System;
using static Godot.Shader;

[GlobalClass]
[Tool]
public partial class Disolve : VisualShaderNodeCustom
{
	public override string _GetName()
	{
		return "Disolve";
	}
	public override string _GetCategory()
	{
		return "CustomShaderNodes";
	}
	public override string _GetDescription()
	{
		return "Disolve effect based on a threshold value";
	}

	public override PortType _GetReturnIconType()
	{
		return PortType.Vector4D;
	}

	public override int _GetInputPortCount()
	{
		return 3;
	}

	public override string _GetInputPortName(int port)
	{
		return port switch
		{
			0 => "NoiseColor",
			1 => "PixelColor",
			2 => "Threshold",
			_ => throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException(nameof(port), "Invalid input port index"),
		};
	}

	public override PortType _GetInputPortType(int port)
	{
		return port switch
		{
			0 => PortType.Vector4D,
			1 => PortType.Vector4D,
			2 => PortType.Scalar,
			_ => throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException(nameof(port), "Invalid input port index"),
		};
	}

	public override int _GetOutputPortCount()
	{
		return 1;
	}

	public override string _GetOutputPortName(int port)
	{
		return "Result";
	}

	public override PortType _GetOutputPortType(int port)
	{
		return PortType.Vector4D;
	}

	public override string _GetGlobalCode(Mode mode)
	{
		return @"
		vec4 disolve(vec4 noise_color, vec4 pixel_color, float threshold) {
			if (noise_color.r > threshold) {
				return vec4(0.0, 0.0, 0.0, 0.0);
			} else {
				return pixel_color;
			}
                }";
	}

	public override string _GetCode(Array<string> inputVars, Array<string> outputVars, Mode mode, VisualShader.Type type)
	{
		return outputVars[0] + " = disolve(" + inputVars[0] + ", " + inputVars[1] + ", " + inputVars[2] + ");";
	}
}
```
2) Within the editor attempt to use it's output while expanding the output options to essentially decompose it.

<img width="146" height="166" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/86d59777-ff78-47bc-9280-bb6f785cd5b4" />

3) Upon building or using the shader, the following error pops within the debugger tab:
```
E 0:00:03:476   get_output_port_type: Index p_port = 4 is out of bounds (output_ports.size() = 1).
  <C++ Source>  scene/resources/visual_shader.cpp:606 @ get_output_port_type()
```


### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

[custom-vs-node-report-project.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/21461928/custom-vs-node-report-project.zip)

### Tested versions

- Reproducible in 4.5beta, 4.5beta.double

### System information

Godot v4.5.beta.double (2d113cc22) - Arch Linux #1 SMP PREEMPT_DYNAMIC Thu, 24 Jul 2025 18:18:11 +0000 on Wayland - Wayland display driver, Multi-window, 2 monitors - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4070 (nvidia; 575.64.05) - AMD Ryzen 9 9950X 16-Core Processor (32 threads) - 154.8 GiB memory

### Issue description

If a shader file contains a struct comparison, then when the editor processes that file, it crashes.

```
shader_type spatial;
struct foo { int x; };
void func () {
  foo a;
  a == a;
}
```

This crashes the editor. If `a == a` is commented out, it does not crash the editor.

### Steps to reproduce

1. Make a project, add a shader file containing the above code.
1. The editor crashes.

